page.title: 11INSECTS OF WYCHWOOD FOREST
page.content: The only scientific study of {INSECTS} to be published by the {NATURE {CONSERVANCY COUNCIL}is on {LARGE MOTHS {-macrolepidoptera-}carried out in 1961 and repeated in 1984. On the first occasion {94 species }were attracted to the 125W mv light trap. In JULY { {1984 136 species }were recorded. Among these were {COMMON EMERALD, {WILLOW BEAUTY, BRIMSTONE,LARGE {ELEPHANT HAWK, YELLOW TAIL, COMMON {FOOTMAN,THE RUSTIC }and the {NUT-TREE {TUSSOCK. { }Large {FRITILLARIES - {Butterflies-}until about {15 years ago were abundant in the forest, but only one sighting since.Among the rarer butterflies to be seen today are { {Green Hairstreaks, Purple Hairstreaks and {White Admirals}.
